&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/philosophy/domains/caribbean/domains/wynterian/>
  rdf:type schema:WebPage ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/philosophy/domains/caribbean/domains/wynterian/> ;
  schema:name "Wynterian Analysis" ;
  schema:description "Sylvia Wynter's analytical framework — the overrepresentation of Man as if it were the human, the genre of the human, the colonial-racial constitution of the modern subject, and the demand for a new science of the human — for understanding how the modern Western subject became the implicit standard against which all other ways of being human are measured and found wanting." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-04-27" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-04-27" ;
  emsenn:Centralthesis "The modern Western secular subject — Man, in two successive overrepresentations (Man1 of the rational political subject, Man2 of the bio-economic subject) — has been overrepresented as if it were the human itself, with the consequence that other genres of the human are rendered subhuman, prehuman, or insufficiently human. The work of decolonization is the work of unsettling this overrepresentation and constructing a new descriptive statement of the human, after Man." ;
  schema:hasPart &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/philosophy/domains/caribbean/domains/wynterian/terms/man-overrepresentation/> , "genres-of-the-human" , "sociogenic-principle" , "descriptive-statement" ;
  emsenn:Locates &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/terms/school/> ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/philosophy/domains/caribbean/domains/wynterian/> .

